You are scoring one team's primary-channel communication against a fixed ontology of communication-pattern features. The ontology was distilled from open-coding many runs of this scenario; your job is to decide, for each ontology category, how strongly this run's primary-channel messages exhibit that feature.

For every category in the ontology below, emit one ``CategoryConfidence`` entry with:
- ``category_id`` — exactly the id from the ontology (case-sensitive).
- ``confidence`` — a float in [0.0, 1.0]. **Score the magnitude of evidence, not your own certainty:**
  - 0.0 — feature is plainly absent across the entire run.
  - ~0.3 — incidental or borderline; maybe one round, ambiguous.
  - ~0.6 — feature appears clearly in multiple rounds but not pervasively.
  - 0.9–1.0 — feature is a dominant, sustained property of the team's protocol.
- ``justification`` — one or two sentences citing specific primary-channel evidence (round numbers, brief quotes) or its absence.

You MUST emit one entry per category, in the order they are listed. Do not skip a category just because the feature is absent — a low confidence with a short "absent" justification is the expected output.

The scenario typically has information asymmetry: different agents see different parts of the per-round ground truth. The per-round ground-truth block below tells you what each agent could see and what the round wanted. Use that when deciding whether the team is encoding scenario-specific values, hand-offs between roles, or neither — and remember that an agent who emits content based on data they cannot see directly must have learned the mapping from earlier primary-channel messages or out-of-band coordination.

